===Verb===
{{en-verb}}

# To [[change]] a [[text]], or a [[document]].
#: ''Your speech is too long. You need to '''edit''' it.''
# To [[alter]] a [[photograph]] or [[recording]] of [[sound]] or [[video]].
#: ''We shot an hour-long interview then '''edited''' it down to 45 minutes.''
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To be the [[editor]] of a publication.
#: ''He '''edits''' the Chronicle.''
#* '''1912''', {{w|L. Frank Baum}}, ''Aunt Jane's Nieces on Vacation'' Chapter 3
#*: "How?" responded Patsy; "why, it's easy enough, Uncle. We'll buy a press, hire a printer, and Beth and Louise will help me '''edit''' the paper. I'm sure I can exhibit literary talents of a high order, once they are encouraged to sprout. Louise writes lovely poetry and 'stories of human interest,' and Beth—"
# {{lb|en|computing}} To change the contents of a [[file]], [[website]], etc.
#: ''Wikipedia is an interactive encyclopedia which allows anybody to '''edit''' and improve articles.''
# {{lb|en|biology}} To [[alter]] the [[DNA]] sequence of a [[chromosome]]; to perform [[gene splicing]].
#* {{quote-journal|en|date=26 April 2015|author=Beth Shapiro|title=Could we 'de-extinctify' the woolly mammoth|newspaper=The Guardian|url=http://www.theguardian.com/science/2015/apr/26/woolly-mammoth-normal-for-norfolk-de-extinction}}
#*: Today, the technology to edit '''genomes''' is limited in the number of changes that can be made at once, which is probably one reason why the Harvard team focused on only 14 genes.
# To [[assemble]] a [[film]] by [[cut]]ting and [[splice|splicing]] raw [[footage]].
#* {{quote-journal|en|date=December 17 2014|author=Mekado Murphy|title=Below the Line: Editing ‘Boyhood’|newspaper=New York Times|url=http://carpetbagger.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/12/17/below-the-line-editing-boyhood/}}
#*: When the director approached Ms. Adair about his idea for “Boyhood,” shooting footage each of those 12 years, she immediately agreed to take part. The decision was made to '''edit''' the film progressively, cutting the scenes from each year after they were completed.
# {{lb|en|comedy}} To cut short or otherwise alter an [[improvised]] scene.
#* {{quote-book|en|title=The Comedy Improv Handbook: A Comprehensive Guide to University Improvisational Comedy in Theatre and Performance|author=Matt Fotis; Siobhan O'Hara|year=2015|publisher=Focal Press|location=New York, NY|isbn=9781315678108|page=145|passage=A good rule of thumb is to '''edit''' a scene before you think, "Gosh, somebody should '''edit''' this scene."}}
# {{lb|en|ergative}} To lend itself to editing in a certain way.
#* '''2018''', Gary Hudson, Sarah Rowlands, ''The Broadcast Journalism Handbook''
#*: The junior can offer to do the voxes, gaining experience and sparing the senior journalist the trouble. Always remember to think how the clips will '''edit''' together.

